    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Making Sense Of Terror Alerts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Henkel letter on Aug 5 editorial holds raising terror alerts in New York City, New Jersey and Washington discourages terrorist attacks there</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 5 editorial does not cite the real reason for the current terror alert: Al Qaeda is known for picking ''soft targets.'' While the terror alert is costly and inconveniences a lot of people and probably hurts businesses, the raising of the alerts in New York City, New Jersey and Washington is sending a clear message to the terrorists: These are no longer ''soft targets.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 5 editorial does not cite the real reason for the current terror alert: Al Qaeda is known for picking ''soft targets.'' While the terror alert is costly and inconveniences a lot of people and probably hurts businesses, the raising of the alerts in New York City, New Jersey and Washington is sending a clear message to the terrorists: These are no longer ''soft targets.''</p>
        <p>If such ''unbelievable'' information had surfaced about terrorists hijacking airplanes to crash into the World Trade Center and the Pentagon, it would have been dismissed as ludicrous, coming from intelligence officials trying to feather their own nests and reputations.</p>
        <p>Nitpicking the competence of the present ''alert,'' as well as implying political motives to government officials, does not do a service to the memories of the nearly 3,000 killed on Sept. 11.</p>
        <p>Robert Henkel  Stratford, Conn., Aug. 5, 2004</p>
      </block>
